00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6 Minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Neil.

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:17.000
And I'm Beth. In our lifetime, one in five people will be affected by cancer.

5
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:22.000
A disease where cells grow uncontrollably and cause tumours in the body.

6
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Chumours can be benign, meaning not cancerous or malignant, meaning cancerous.

7
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:37.000
And in 2022, there were an estimated 9.7 million deaths from malignant cancers worldwide.

8
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:41.000
But in this program, we'll be focusing on some good news instead.

9
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Vaccines are medicine which protects the human body by making it immune from a certain disease.

10
00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:54.000
And now there's been a sudden and important discovery, a breakthrough in the development of a new vaccine called mRNA.

11
00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.000
So, could a vaccine for cancer soon become a reality?

12
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:04.000
That's what we'll be finding out as well as learning some useful new words and phrases.

13
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:10.000
And remember, if you like listening to 6 Minute English and want to read along at the same time,

14
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:16.000
you can find a transcript for the program on our website, bbcLearningEnglish.com

15
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:25.000
Now I have a question for you, Beth. We've mentioned some of the most recent vaccines, but which disease did the first successful vaccine treat?

16
00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Was it a flu, bbulio, or c smallpox?

17
00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Ooh, I'm going to say polio.

18
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.000
Okay, well we'll find out the correct answer at the end of the program.

19
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:41.000
You might wonder why the body's immune system doesn't fight cancer automatically.

20
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:50.000
The reason is that cancer has clever ways of hiding from unnatural defenses as Dr. Meredith McKeen, director of research at Tennessee on ecology,

21
00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:54.000
explained to bbc world service program the inquiry.

22
00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:01.000
There's been a number of studies that have demonstrated the different techniques that the cancer has developed

23
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:07.000
to be able to put up signals or proteins essentially on the surface of the cancer cells

24
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:12.000
to tell the immune system go away. There's nothing here to look at.

25
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:20.000
And so it's actually been hijacking these receptors to essentially tell the immune system to kind of take the breaks off

26
00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:27.000
and be more aggressive in fighting cancer that's really allowed a breakthrough with the immune therapy over the past decade.

27
00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:33.000
Dr. McKeen says that a number of studies have demonstrated how cancer spreads.

28
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:40.000
She uses the phrase a number of to mean several, but it also makes her statement more convincing

29
00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:44.000
because of course several studies are better than just one.

30
00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:49.000
Cancer cells switch off the immune system by pretending to be healthy cells.

31
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.000
It's like they're saying nothing to see here.

32
00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:57.000
An informal phrase which can be used to encourage people to move or look away from something

33
00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.000
either in a playful way or to cover something up.

34
00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:06.000
For example, a police officer at a crime scene might say nothing to see here to move people on.

35
00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:10.000
So in other words, cancer hijacks healthy cells.

36
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:16.000
It takes control of something which doesn't belong to it and uses it for its own advantage.

37
00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:19.000
So how would a vaccine change things?

38
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:24.000
Well, existing treatments like chemotherapy are aggressively target the cancer,

39
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
but also attack healthy tissue creating unpleasant side effects.

40
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:34.000
New breakthrough vaccines on the other hand retrain the immune system to recognize cancer cells

41
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:41.000
and eliminate those and only those naturally, even in patients with the disease already.

42
00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:46.000
Here's Professor Eduardo Sanchez of the Anderson Cancer Center in Texas,

43
00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:50.000
explaining more to BBC World Services the inquiry.

44
00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:54.000
Basically, the cancer cell started telling the immune system Donna Takumi,

45
00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Don't eat me, right?

46
00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:03.000
The immune system has forgotten how to go about recognizing those cancer cells,

47
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:09.000
becoming blind to recognize those operations that cancer cells generate.

48
00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:16.000
And what we want to do with vaccines is to re-evaluate the immune system.

49
00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:21.000
In cancer patients, the immune system is blind to cancerous growths.

50
00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:26.000
It completely fails to notice them or be aware of their danger.

51
00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:31.000
So the vaccine re-educates the immune system or teaches it to behave in a different way.

52
00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:37.000
To recap, some cancer treatments work by unblocking our blocked natural defenses,

53
00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:43.000
whereas vaccines retrain the immune system to find an attack cancer cells naturally.

54
00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:48.000
Because these two approaches are quite different, they can be used together and individually.

55
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:54.000
So to answer my original question, Neil, a vaccine for cancer might not be too far away.

56
00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:58.000
But how about your question, isn't it time you revealed the answer?

57
00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.000
I asked which disease was first successfully treated by a vaccine.

58
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:04.000
And I said, polio was I right.

59
00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:09.000
You were wrong, I'm afraid, the correct option was C, which is smallpox.

60
00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned in this program starting with breakthrough,

61
00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.000
a sudden dramatic and important discovery.

62
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:24.000
A number of something means several or many and can add credibility to what you say.

63
00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:32.000
The phrase nothing to see here is used to discourage people from paying attention or looking to closely at something or to move them away.

64
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:38.000
If you hijack something, you use something that doesn't belong to you for your own benefits.

65
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:43.000
Being blind to something means failing to notice it or recognize it as a threat.

66
00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:50.000
And finally to re-educate means to teach somebody to think or behave in a new or different way.

67
00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.000
Once again, our six minutes are up.

